# Testing Discipline

Tests are the acceptance contract. They must actually catch bugs (mutation gate).

## Every test

- Binds its requirement(s): `req.Covers(t, "REQ-...")` as the first line.
- Is deterministic: inject `clock.NewFake(...)` and `idgen.NewSequence(...)`.
  Never `time.Sleep` to "wait"; advance the fake clock instead.
- No network, no real daemons in unit tests; use fakes / the hermetic harness.

```go
func TestThing(t *testing.T) {
    req.Covers(t, "REQ-XXX-001")
    rc := reqctx.New(clock.NewFake(time.Unix(0,0)), idgen.NewSequence("t"))
    // given / when / then, deterministic assertions
}
```

## Strength (anti-gaming)

- Prefer table-driven tests; add property/invariant tests for billing, idempotency
  and shadow (`pgregory.net/rapid` when useful).
- Assert on boundaries (e.g. `<=` vs `<`) so mutation testing cannot survive.
- NEVER use `t.Skip`, weaken an assertion, or edit a `*.golden` to make CI pass.
  If behavior legitimately changed, update the golden in its own change with a note.
